{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17529868","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17529868"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:59:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:59:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14469"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14469","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14469"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.68,0.09,0.12,0.07,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7164"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107178"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7164","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7164"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14469"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89633"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"483"},{"type":"tags","id":"1122"},{"type":"tags","id":"2253"},{"type":"tags","id":"2705"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4922"},{"type":"tags","id":"12917"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17183"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39723"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107178","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107178"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old man is admitted to the Intensive Care Unit with an acute exacerbation of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD). He has a medical history of severe COPD, hypertension, and type 2 diabetes. His regular medications include tiotropium, fluticasone/salmeterol inhaler, metformin, and amlodipine. On examination, he appears distressed with increased work of breathing. \u003Cbr /\u003EHis vital signs are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPulse rate 110/min\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood pressure 145/90 mmHg\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERespiratory rate 32/min\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESpO2 88% on 4 L/min oxygen via nasal cannula\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETemperature 37.2\u00b0C.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChest auscultation reveals diffuse wheezes and prolonged expiration. Despite initial treatment with nebulised bronchodilators and systemic corticosteroids, his condition is worsening. \u003Cbr /\u003EArterial blood gas analysis shows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EpH 7.28 (7.35-7.45)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPaCO2 68 mmHg (35-45)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPaO2 58 mmHg (75-100)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHCO3- 30 mmol/L (22-26)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Initiate non-invasive ventilation","Perform endotracheal intubation","Start intravenous magnesium sulphate","Increase oxygen flow rate","Administer intravenous aminophylline"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with an acute exacerbation of COPD complicated by acute hypercapnic (type 2) respiratory failure, as evidenced by the increased work of breathing, tachypnoea, and arterial blood gas results showing respiratory acidosis with hypercapnia. In this scenario, the most appropriate next step in management is to \u003Cstrong\u003Einitiate non-invasive ventilation (NIV)\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENIV is the first-line treatment for acute hypercapnic respiratory failure in COPD exacerbations. It has been shown to reduce the need for intubation, decrease length of hospital stay, and improve mortality rates. NIV works by reducing the work of breathing, improving gas exchange, and allowing respiratory muscles to rest. It is particularly beneficial in patients with COPD exacerbations who have failed to respond adequately to initial medical therapy, as in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreasing the oxygen flow rate\u003C/strong\u003E would not be an appropriate management strategy in this situation. While the patient is hypoxemic, increasing oxygen flow without addressing the underlying hypercapnia could worsen respiratory acidosis and potentially lead to CO2 narcosis. In COPD patients with a known history of CO2 retention, the goal is to maintain SpO2 between 88-92% to avoid worsening hypercapnia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdministering intravenous aminophylline\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended as a first-line treatment in COPD exacerbations due to its narrow therapeutic window and potential for significant side effects. Current guidelines do not routinely recommend its use in this setting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndotracheal intubation\u003C/strong\u003E and mechanical ventilation should be reserved for patients who fail NIV or have contraindications to NIV. It carries significant risks, including ventilator-associated pneumonia and prolonged ICU stay. NIV should be attempted first in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous magnesium sulphate\u003C/strong\u003E is sometimes used in severe asthma exacerbations but is not a standard treatment for COPD exacerbations. While it may have some bronchodilator effects, it would not address the primary issue of respiratory failure in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter initiating NIV, close monitoring of the patient\u0027s respiratory status, blood gases, and comfort level is essential. If the patient fails to improve with NIV, intubation and mechanical ventilation may become necessary. Additionally, ongoing management should include continued bronchodilator therapy, systemic corticosteroids, and treatment of any underlying infections if present.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Non-invasive ventilation (NIV) is the first-line ventilation strategy for acute hypercapnic respiratory failure in COPD exacerbations.","NIV reduces the need for intubation, length of hospital stay, and mortality in COPD patients with acute respiratory failure.","Careful monitoring of respiratory rate, blood gases, and patient comfort is essential when initiating NIV."],"references":["Elshof J, Vonk JM, van der Pouw A, van Dijk C, Vos P, Kerstjens HAM, Wijkstra PJ, Duiverman ML. Clinical practice of non-invasive ventilation for acute exacerbations of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease. Respir Res. 2023 Aug 23;24(1):208. doi: 10.1186/s12931-023-02507-1. PMID: 37612749; PMCID: PMC10464197. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10464197/","Coleman JM 3rd, Wolfe LF, Kalhan R. Noninvasive Ventilation in Chronic Obstructive Pulmonary Disease. Ann Am Thorac Soc. 2019 Sep;16(9):1091-1098. doi: 10.1513/AnnalsATS.201810-657CME. PMID: 31185181. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31185181/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89633"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14469"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89633","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89633"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-25T21:33:22+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-25T21:34:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7164"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107178"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"26","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/26"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd7c","name":"Critical Care Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/78"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level III","synonyms":null,"description":"Apply, analyze, evaluate, and create (implementing, organizing, and critiquing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"483","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/483"},"attributes"